mainmatter.p:
The module of Kähler differentials of a ring map A \to B is a B-module \Omega _{B/A} together with an A-derivation \mathrm{d} : B \to \Omega _{B/A}, defined equivalently by one of the following:
(universal property) it represents the covariant functor \operatorname{Mod} _B \to \operatorname{Set} by M \mapsto \operatorname{Der} _A(B,M);
(construction) it is the free B-module generated by symbols \mathrm{d} b, for b \in B, modulo the submodule generated by \mathrm{d} a (a \in A), \mathrm{d} (b+b')- \mathrm{d} b - \mathrm{d} b', and \mathrm{d} (bb') - b \mathrm{d} b' - b' \mathrm{d} b;
(diagonal) it is I/I^2 where I = \ker (B \otimes _A B \xrightarrow{b \otimes b' \mapsto bb'} B), and \mathrm{d} : B \to I/I^2 is given by b \mapsto 1 \otimes b - b \otimes 1.

The module of Kähler differentials of a ring map A \to B is a B-module \Omega _{B/A} together with an A-derivation \mathrm{d} : B \to \Omega _{B/A}, defined equivalently by one of the following:
(universal property) it represents the covariant functor \operatorname{Mod} _B \to \operatorname{Set} by M \mapsto \operatorname{Der} _A(B,M);
(construction) it is the free B-module generated by symbols \mathrm{d} b, for b \in B, modulo the submodule generated by \mathrm{d} a (a \in A), \mathrm{d} (b+b')- \mathrm{d} b - \mathrm{d} b', and \mathrm{d} (bb') - b \mathrm{d} b' - b' \mathrm{d} b;
(diagonal) it is I/I^2 where I = \ker (B \otimes _A B \xrightarrow{b \otimes b' \mapsto bb'} B), and \mathrm{d} : B \to I/I^2 is given by b \mapsto 1 \otimes b - b \otimes 1.
